cs.NE, cs.DS, cs.IT, cs.DM, cs.CC

This paper is about drift analysis, a technique used in the runtime analysis of randomized search heuristics (RSHs) such as evolutionary algorithms and simulated annealing. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). The paper also deals with tail bounds, which are a topic in probability theory and statistics, suggesting that cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.IT (Information Theory) are also likely categories. The paper also mentions benchmark problems and random permutations, indicating that it could belong to cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
